immoral. On 18 June 2006, the Montenegrin parliament voted to include abortion as an European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR)-protected right under its new Criminal Code.

On the same day, the Montenegrin parliament adopted the Law on Abortion—a codification of the Criminal Code on abortion taking effect on 8 October 2006. Montenegro’s criminal code protects the rights of a pregnant woman seeking to terminate her pregnancy. The criminal code allows terminations of pregnancies before 12 weeks and after that, only under the circumstances set out in it. This includes, among other scenarios, if the pregnancy may present serious risk to the woman’s health or life or if the pregnancy was the result of rape or of the criminal offence of incest (sexual intercourse between parents and children or siblings). Art.

335 when applied in cases of rape may represent a situation of extra-legal punishment of women who chose to abort or give birth after enduring a period of pregnancy with consequences for their reproductive health and dignity. Laws on abortion in Montenegro and Serbia & Montenegro;

There is nothing sacramental about an abortion.

Under the provision, termination of a pregnancy by the mother during the first 12 weeks is considered an ordinary offence, while after this period it is an aggravated offence. The main alteration by the parliament in the new text was to abolish criminal punishment for doctors performing abortions for medical, family and other reasons when a woman is in extremely distressing circumstances.

Republic of Serbia
